<canvas class="hidden stagger-4" height="40" id="tape-timeline"></canvas>
<p class="info-text hidden stagger-5">
        Brian Eno and Terry Riley pioneered tape loop composition in the 1960s–70s. By using loops
        of different, non-integer-related lengths, the system creates combinatorial variation that
        takes hours or days to repeat. <em>Music for Airports</em> (1978) used loops of 17.8, 20.25,
        and 22.5 seconds — their LCM produces 80+ minutes before exact repetition.
      </p>
