<p class="info-text hidden stagger-3" id="dl-info-text" style="text-align:left;">
        Pauline Oliveros (1932–2016) developed Deep Listening as a practice: attending to sounds of
        all kinds, both environmental and imaginary. "Deep listening is a practice that is intended
        to heighten and expand consciousness of sound in as many dimensions of awareness and
        attentional dynamics as possible." Her practice retreats were held in large reverberant
        spaces — caves, cisterns, tunnels. The practice asks: what sounds were here before you
        arrived? What will remain after you leave?
      </p>
