<!-- SECTION 10 / GLOSSARY                                               -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="section-sep"></div>
<section id="glossary">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden stagger-1">
<p class="section-num">10 / GLOSSARY</p>
<h2>The<br/>Language</h2>
<p class="thesis">The language of systems and patience.</p>
</div>
<div class="glossary-grid hidden stagger-2">
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Ambient Music</div><div class="gloss-def">Music intended to create atmosphere rather than direct attention. It coexists with ambient sound without competing. Coined by Eno in 1978.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">System Music</div><div class="gloss-def">Music created by defining a process or set of rules, then letting the system run. The composer sets the conditions; the music unfolds autonomously.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Generative Music</div><div class="gloss-def">Music that is algorithmically created in real time, never repeating exactly. Every listening is a unique performance. Eno's term for the practice.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Drone</div><div class="gloss-def">A sustained, unchanging (or slowly evolving) pitch or chord. Found in Indian classical music, Celtic music, and all ambient traditions. The musical equivalent of geological time.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Tape Loop</div><div class="gloss-def">A length of magnetic tape spliced end-to-end to repeat indefinitely. The foundation of early ambient and minimalist composition — physical, tactile, irreversible.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Phase Shifting</div><div class="gloss-def">Running two identical patterns at slightly different speeds until they drift apart, creating complex textures from simple material. Developed by Steve Reich.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Feedback</div><div class="gloss-def">Routing the output of a system back into its input. In audio: self-sustaining resonance. Below unity gain: controlled drone. Above unity gain: runaway oscillation.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Shimmer Reverb</div><div class="gloss-def">Reverb with a pitch-shifted feedback path — typically an octave up. The decay generates harmonically elevated copies of itself, creating the shimmer characteristic of ambient music.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Deep Listening</div><div class="gloss-def">Pauline Oliveros's practice of total, non-selective sonic attention. Listening to everything — environmental, internal, imaginary — simultaneously and without hierarchy.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Probability</div><div class="gloss-def">Using random numbers to decide whether a musical event occurs. A 50% cell fires approximately half the time. Probability creates unpredictable patterns from fixed structures.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">LCM</div><div class="gloss-def">Lowest Common Multiple. The smallest number divisible by two or more integers. For tape loops of 7 and 11 beats, the LCM is 77 — when they finally coincide.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Process Composition</div><div class="gloss-def">Composition by defining a transformation rule and applying it consistently. The process is the piece. Steve Reich's "Music as a Gradual Process" (1968) is the manifesto.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Field Recording</div><div class="gloss-def">Audio captured in real acoustic environments — forests, cities, bodies of water. Used as raw material or finished composition. The world as instrument.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Soundscape</div><div class="gloss-def">The acoustic environment of a place, as a whole. R. Murray Schafer coined the term; his World Soundscape Project documented vanishing acoustic ecologies in the 1970s.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Psychoacoustic</div><div class="gloss-def">The perception of sound by the human auditory system. Ambient music exploits psychoacoustics: sum tones, difference tones, and beating frequencies emerge from simple inputs.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Non-Developmental Form</div><div class="gloss-def">Music that does not build toward a climax or conclusion. It simply is, at any point in its duration. Ambient music perfected this: no beginning-middle-end arc.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Environmental Music</div><div class="gloss-def">Music designed for a specific physical space and purpose — airports, lobbies, gardens. Satie's "furniture music" (1920) is the origin; Eno's airport commissions the maturity.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Stasis</div><div class="gloss-def">Musical stillness — the absence of directed harmonic motion. Ambient music often sustains a single harmonic state indefinitely. Stasis as content, not failure of movement.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Spectral</div><div class="gloss-def">Relating to the frequency spectrum of a sound. Spectral composers (Grisey, Murail) base harmonic language on acoustic overtone series. Ambient music is inherently spectral in approach.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-card"><div class="gloss-term">Continuous Form</div><div class="gloss-def">Music with no discrete sections, movements, or formal boundaries. It flows without articulation. The listener can enter or exit at any point without losing orientation — there is no orientation to lose.</div></div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
